# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: philadelphia-athletics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] The **$100,000 infield** was the infield of the Philadelphia Athletics in the early 1910s.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield consisted of first baseman Stuffy McInnis, second baseman Eddie Collins, shortstop Jack Barry and third baseman Frank "Home Run" Baker.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] According to the *Encyclopædia Britannica*, the nickname reflects "the purported combined market value of the foursome", which is equivalent to about $2.44 million in 2024.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Baseball historian Bill James rated the 1914 edition of the $100,000 infield the greatest infield of all time, and also ranked the 1912 and 1913 editions in the top five all time.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] The $100,000 infield helped the Athletics win four American League championships in five years—1910, 1911, 1913 and 1914—and win the World Series in 1910, 1911 and 1913.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] The group was broken up after losing the 1914 World Series as a result of the financial pressures resulting from the emergence of the Federal League.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Two members—Collins and Baker—have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Collins was the first member of the $100,000 infield to join the Athletics.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He debuted on September 17, 1906, after playing college ball at Columbia University.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] In 1906 and 1907, he played 20 games for the Athletics, mostly at shortstop.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] In 1908, he took over as the Athletics' regular second baseman, replacing Danny Murphy, who moved to the outfield.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] During the $100,000 infield years from 1910 to 1914, he played 738 games, getting 922 hits in 2,677 at bats for a batting average of .344.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He led the American League in runs in 1912, 1913 and 1914, stolen bases in 1910, singles in 1913 and times on base in 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in the American League in batting average, on-base percentage, hits, stolen bases, singles and times on base every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] In addition, he finished in the top ten in American Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, winning the Most Valuable Player award in 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Chicago White Sox after the 1914 season as Athletics' manager Connie Mack attempted to respond to the financial pressures brought on by the newly formed Federal League, breaking up the $100,000 infield.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He returned to Mack and the Athletics in 1927, finishing his career playing 12 games for the Athletics in their 1929 and 1930 World Championship seasons.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1939.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Barry was the next to join the Athletics, debuting on July 13, 1908, after playing for the College of the Holy Cross.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Barry played 686 games for the Athletics, getting 607 hits in 2,334 at bats for a batting average of .260.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He finished in the American League top ten in sacrifice hits every year from 1911 through 1914, and ranked fifth in the American League in runs batted in in 1913.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] But his primary contributions were on defense, where he had a strong arm, enormous range and sure hands, and was able to work out innovative plays with his good friend Collins, such as a defense against the double steal.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He finished in the top 20 in Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, with his best showing a ninth-place finish in 1913.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He was sold to the Boston Red Sox in the middle of the 1915 season, where he moved to second base and played on the Red Sox' 1915 and 1916 World Championship teams.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He missed the Red Sox 1918 Championship season due to service in the U.S.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Baker also joined the Athletics in 1908, debuting on September 21.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He became the Athletics regular third baseman in 1909, and led the American League in triples that season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, Baker played 742 games for the Athletics, getting 929 hits in 2,864 at bats for a batting average of .324.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He led the American League in home runs every year from 1911 through 1914, and led the league in runs batted in during 1912 and 1913.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He also finished in the top ten in batting average, slugging percentage, on-base percentage and times on base every year from 1911 through 1914, and finished in the top ten in runs scored, hits, doubles, total bases, extra base hits and runs batted in every year from 1910 through 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He finished in the top ten in the American League Most Valuable Player voting every year from 1911 through 1914, finishing third in 1914, his highest showing.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Baker was the hero of the 1911 World Series, hitting two home runs to help the Athletics win the series, which earned him the nickname "Home Run" Baker.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Baker held out the 1915 season when manager and owner Connie Mack refused to increase his salary, and was sold to the New York Yankees in 1916 after American League president Ban Johnson intervened.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He finished his career as the third baseman for the Yankees pennant-winning teams in 1921 and 1922.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Baker was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1955.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] McInnis was the final member of the $100,000 infield to join.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He started his career as an 18-year-old little-used backup infielder for the Athletics in 1909, and played a little more in 1910.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] In 1909 and 1910, he played more games backing up Barry at shortstop than at any other position.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Before the 1911 season, Mack decided to make McInnis his regular first baseman, replacing the popular veteran Harry Davis, although McInnis did have to begin the season as the Athletics' shortstop when Barry became ill before taking over at first base.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Defensively as a first baseman, he was known for having exceptional reach.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Between 1910 and 1914, McInnis played 614 games for the Athletics, getting 715 hits in 2,228 at bats for a batting average of .321.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He led the American League in singles in 1914, and finished in the top ten in batting average, hits, total bases, runs batted in and singles every year from 1912 through 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] In both 1912 and 1913, he also finished in the top ten in slugging percentage and on-base percentage.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He received Most Valuable Player votes every season from 1911 through 1914, finishing seventh in both 1913 and 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] McInnis is the only member of the $100,000 infield to remain with the Athletics beyond 1915.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He was eventually traded to the Boston Red Sox in 1918 in exchange for Larry Gardner, Hick Cady and Tilly Walker, where he played on Boston's 1918 World Championship team.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] He also reteamed with Barry on the 1919 Boston Red Sox.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/100-000-infield] Before finishing his career in 1927 he also played with the Cleveland Indians, Boston Braves, Pittsburgh Pirates and Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1901 Philadelphia Athletics season** involved the A's finishing fourth in the American League with a record of 74 wins and 62 losses.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The franchise that would become the modern Athletics originated in 1901 as a new franchise in the American League.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Western League had been renamed the American League in 1900 by league president Bancroft (Ban) Johnson, and declared itself the second major league in 1901.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Johnson created new franchises in the east and eliminated some franchises in the west.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Philadelphia seems to have been a new franchise created to compete with the National League's Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Former catcher Connie Mack was recruited to manage the club.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Mack in turn persuaded Phillies minority owner Ben Shibe as well as others to invest in the team, which would be called the **Philadelphia Athletics**.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] He himself bought a 25 percent interest.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1901, Nap Lajoie jumped from the Phillies to the crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, owned by Connie Mack.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie's batting average that year was .426, still a league record.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1901-philadelphia-athletics-season] The same year Lajoie became the second major leaguer to be intentionally walked with the bases loaded after Abner Dalrymple in 1881.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The **1902 major league baseball season** was contested from April 17 through October 5, 1902.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American League (AL), with the Philadelphia Athletics winning the AL pennant.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant for the second consecutive season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Milwaukee Brewers moved and became the St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns; the franchise would remain in St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis through 1953, and in 1954 moved again to become the modern Baltimore Orioles.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This season would be the last of this season's Baltimore Orioles, who would fold following the conclusion of the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues renamed as the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The 1902 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with every team playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 19, with a one-off game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Boston Americans, with the rest of the season beginning April 23.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 29, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games (8 in AL, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Across both leagues, Sammy Strang tied as a leader in runs at 109 (108 with the Chicago White Stockings of the AL and 1 with the Chicago Orphans of the NL).
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds leave League Park (where they played for 18 seasons) and move to the Palace of the Fans, where they would go on to play for ten seasons through 1911.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The **1903 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1903.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Boston Americans as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first modern World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Americans defeated the Pirates, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the World Series, following the one-off 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first inter-league series since the 1890 World's Championship Series between the National League and defunct-since-1891 American Association.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 World Series would also mark the first championship series that is still celebrated today, as all previous series are considered pre-modern and these early contests are discussed by MLB and baseball historians separately.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] However, the 1903 arrangement was primarily between the two participating clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues, essentially making this season's World Series a voluntary event.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The defunct Baltimore Orioles were replaced by a new franchise in New York City known as the New York Highlanders; it was the last change to the lineup of AL and NL franchises until 1953.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns relocated there as a new Baltimore Orioles in 1954.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Orphans and Cleveland Bronchos were renamed as the Chicago Cubs and Cleveland Naps, respectively.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see an increase of games played.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 16 with four teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 20, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston Americans.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the American League would see its final day of the season on September 29.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The inaugural World Series took place between October 1 and October 13.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (6 in AL, 9 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Americans defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series in eight games.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Termed the "Battle of Ohio", the Cincinnati Reds and Cleveland Naps played an unofficial best of 11-game exhibition series after the regular season, with Cleveland winning the series six games to three.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the enfranchisement of the New York Highlanders, in place of the folded Baltimore Orioles, playing at Hilltop Park in New York City, New York, where they would play for ten seasons through 1912.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] On August 8, in what is known as the worst disaster in American sports spectating history, Black Saturday, a section of balcony at the Philadelphia Phillies' home at the Baker Bowl collapsed, killing 12 spectators and injuring 232.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies played the last 16 of their 61 home games at the home of the American League crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, Columbia Park from August 20.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1903 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 75 wins and 60 losses, 14½ games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The A's had begun play in 1901 but National League and American League teams did not play each other in 1901 or 1902 as the leagues battled to expand their markets and customers.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] After the leagues made peace after 1902, the Phillies and Athletics scheduled a preseason series for the local championship.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Player League’s Philadelphia Athletics and American Association Athletics had contested the local championship with the Phillies between 1883 and 1890.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] Prior to the start of the series, the Athletics players threatened not to play unless they were paid a percentage of the gate receipts.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Phillies and Athletics played five of nine scheduled games; the Phillies defeated the Athletics, 4 games to 1.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The series was scheduled to begin on April 4, 1903 at the Phillies’ Philadelphia Ball Park but was called off due to rain.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] Games scheduled for April 7, 1903 at the Phillies’ park and April 8, 1903 at the Athletics’ Columbia Park were also canceled due to rain and wet grounds, along with the final scheduled game of the series on April 14, 1903 at the Phillies’ park.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Philadelphia Phillies and Athletics played a postseason series for the local championship in addition to the preseason series played in April.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The teams played seven of ten games scheduled; games scheduled for October 8, 1903; October 9, 1903; and October 10, 1903 were canceled due to rain.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Athletics won the series, 4 games to 3.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] All of the series games were played at the Athletics’ Columbia Park with each team alternating as the home team.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] The Phillies’ Philadelphia Ball Park’s had collapsed on August 8 1903 leaving four dead, and closing the ballpark for the balance of the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/1903-philadelphia-athletics-season] After the 1903 season, the Phillies had won 7 and the Athletics had won 5 of the 12 total games played in the city series.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The **Philadelphia Athletics** were a Major League Baseball team that played in Philadelphia from 1901 to 1954, when they moved to Kansas City, Missouri, and became the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] After another move to Oakland, California, in 1967, they became the Oakland Athletics.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 2025, the team moved to West Sacramento, California, as the Athletics, and plans ultimately to move to the Las Vegas metropolitan area.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Philadelphia Athletics had an overall win–loss record of 3,886–4,248–79 (.478) during their 54 years in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Eight former Philadelphia Athletics players were elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Western League was renamed the American League in 1900 by league president Bancroft (Ban) Johnson and declared itself the second major league in 1901.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Johnson created new franchises in the east and eliminated some franchises in the west.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Philadelphia was given a new franchise to compete with the National League's Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack in turn persuaded Phillies minority owner Ben Shibe as well as others to invest in the team, which would be called the Philadelphia Athletics, a name taken from the Athletic Base Ball Club of Philadelphia, which had been a founding member of the NL in 1876 but had folded after only one season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack himself bought a 25% interest, while the remaining 25% was sold to Philadelphia sportswriters Sam Jones and Frank Hough.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The new league recruited many of its players from the existing National League, persuading them to "jump" to the American League in defiance of their contracts.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] One of the players who jumped to the new league was second baseman Nap Lajoie, formerly of the crosstown Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] He won the A.L.'s first batting title with a .426 batting average, still a league record.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics and the American League received a setback when, on April 21, 1902, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court invalidated Lajoie's contract with the Athletics, and ordered him back to the Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] This order, though, was only enforceable in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Lajoie was sold to Cleveland, but was kept out of road games in Philadelphia until the National Agreement was signed between the two leagues in 1903.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Columbia Park was the Athletics first home.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] They played there from their founding in 1901 through the 1908 season, and it was the venue of their two home games in the 1905 World Series.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In the early years, the Athletics established themselves as one of the dominant teams in the new league, winning the A.L. pennant six times (1902, 1905, 1910, 1911, 1913, and 1914), and winning the World Series in 1910, 1911, and 1913.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The team was known for its "$100,000 infield," consisting of Stuffy McInnis (first base), Eddie Collins (second base), Jack Barry (shortstop), and Frank "Home Run" Baker (third base) as well as pitchers Eddie Plank and Chief Bender.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Rube Waddell was also a major pitching star for the Athletics in the early 1900s.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] According to Lamont Buchanan in *The World Series and Highlights of Baseball*, the Athletics fans were fond of chanting, "If Eddie Plank doesn't make you lose / We have Waddell and Bender all ready to use!" Plank holds the franchise record for career victories, with 284.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1909, the Athletics moved into the major leagues' first concrete-and-steel ballpark, Shibe Park.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] This remains the second and last time in franchise history where a new ballpark was built specifically for the Athletics.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1912, Mack bought the 25% of the team's stock owned by Jones and Hough to become a full partner with Shibe.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Shibe ceded Mack full control over the baseball side while retaining control over the business side.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, Mack had already enjoyed a nearly free hand in baseball matters since the franchise's inception.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1914, the Athletics lost the 1914 World Series to the "Miracle Braves" in a four-game sweep.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack traded, sold or released most of the team's star players soon after.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In his book *To Every Thing a Season*, Bruce Kuklick points out that there were suspicions that the Athletics had thrown the Series, or at least "laid down," perhaps in protest of Mack's frugal ways.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack himself alluded to that rumor years later, but debunked it.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] He claimed that the team was torn by numerous internal factions, and was also distracted by the allure of a third major league, the Federal League.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Federal League had been formed to begin play in 1914.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] As the AL had done 13 years before, the new league raided existing AL and NL teams for players.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Several of his best players, including Bender, had already decided to jump before the World Series.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack refused to match the upstart league's offers, preferring to rebuild with younger (and less expensive) players.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The result was a swift and near-total collapse.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics went from a 99–53 (.651) record and a pennant in 1914 to a record of 43–109 (.283) and last place in 1915, and then to 36–117 (.235, still a modern major-league low) in 1916.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The team would finish in last place every year through 1922 and would not contend again until 1925.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Shibe died in 1922, and his sons Tom and John took over the business side, leaving the baseball side to Mack.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Although Mack only held the titles of vice president and secretary-treasurer, for all intents and purposes he was now the head of the franchise and would remain so for the next three decades.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] By this time, Mack had cemented his famous image of the tall, gaunt and well-dressed man waving his players into position with a scorecard.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Unlike most managers, he chose to wear a high-collar shirt, tie, ascot scarf, and a straw boater hat instead of a uniform, a look that he never changed for the rest of his life, even decades after it went out of fashion.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] This came at the price of Mack not being allowed on-field during games per league regulations.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] By the latter half of the 1920s, Mack had assembled one of the most feared batting orders in the history of baseball, featuring three future Baseball Hall of Fame members.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] At its heart were Al Simmons, who batted .334 and hit 307 home runs over his major league career, Jimmie Foxx, who hit 30 or more home runs in 12 consecutive seasons and drove in more than 100 runs in 13 consecutive years, and Mickey Cochrane, one of the best-hitting catchers in baseball history.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] A fourth future Hall of Fame member was pitcher Lefty Grove, who led the American League in strikeouts seven years in a row, and had the league's lowest earned run average a record nine times.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1927 and 1928, the Athletics finished second to the New York Yankees, then won pennants in 1929, 1930 and 1931, winning the World Series in 1929 and 1930.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In each of the three years, the Athletics won over 100 games.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] While the 1927 New York Yankees, whose batting order was known as the Murderers' Row, are remembered as one of the best teams in baseball history, the Athletics teams of the late 1920s and early 1930s are largely forgotten.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Opponents who faced both teams considered them to be generally equal.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Both teams won three consecutive pennants and two of three World Series.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Statistically the New York and Philadelphia dynasties were remarkably even: The Athletics had a record of 313–143 (.686) between 1929 and 1931; the Yankees, 302–160 (.654) between 1926 and 1928.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] And while the Athletics scored six fewer runs than the Yankees (2,710–2,716), the Athletics had five fewer runs scored against them (1,992–1,997), a combined difference of only one run.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Yankees had the best single season at the plate, hitting for a combined .307 batting average and scoring 975 runs in 1927.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics' strongest offensive performance came in 1929, when they batted .296.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] On defense the Athletics were clearly superior; over their three-year American League reign they committed only 432 errors, 167 fewer than the Yankees.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Cochrane was also especially adept at telling his pitchers how to pitch to opposing batters.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Many veteran baseball observers believe that the Yankees' far more exalted status in history is due largely to the fact that they played in New York, where most of the national media is located.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] As it turned out, this would be the Athletics' last hurrah in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Great Depression was well under way, and declining attendance drastically reduced the team's revenues.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack again sold or traded his best players in order to reduce expenses.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In September 1932, he sold Simmons, Jimmy Dykes and Mule Haas to the Chicago White Sox for $100,000.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In December 1933, Mack sent Grove, Rube Walberg and Max Bishop to the Boston Red Sox for Bob Kline, Rabbit Warstler and $125,000.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Also in 1933, he sold Cochrane to the Detroit Tigers for $100,000.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The construction of a spite fence at Shibe Park, blocking the view from nearby buildings, only served to irritate potential paying fans.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, the consequences did not become apparent for a few more years, as the team finished second in 1932 and third in 1933.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack was already 68 years old when the Athletics won the pennant in 1931, and many felt that the game had long since passed him by.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Although he had every intention of building another winner, he did not have the extra money to get big stars.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] He also did not (or could not) invest in a farm system.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Unlike most other owners, Mack had no source of income apart from the Athletics, so the dwindling attendance figures of the early 1930s hit him especially hard.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] As a result, the Athletics went into a decline that lasted for over 30 years, through three cities.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics finished fifth in 1934, then last in 1935.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Except for a fifth-place finish in 1944, they finished in last or next-to-last place every year through 1946.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Tom Shibe died in 1936 and John succeeded him as club president.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, John resigned due to illness a few months later, leaving the presidency to Mack.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] When John died on July 11, 1937, Mack bought enough shares from the Shibe estate to become majority owner.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, Mack had been the franchise's number-one man since Ben Shibe's death.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Even as bad as the Athletics got during this time, Mack retained full authority over business and baseball matters.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Long after most teams hired a general manager, Mack continued making all personnel decisions and leading the team on the field.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] One of the few times that he even considered ceding some of his duties came in the 1934–35 offseason, when the Athletics were not far removed from what would be their last great era.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] He seriously entertained hiring Babe Ruth to succeed him as manager, but backed off from this idea, saying that the Babe's wife, Claire, would be running the team within a month.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Even when the Phillies moved to Shibe Park as tenants of the Athletics midway through the 1938 season, not enough revenue came in for Mack to build another winner.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] By the mid-1940s, as Mack passed his 80th birthday, he was showing unmistakable signs of mental deterioration, almost to the point of senility.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] He would frequently sleep through innings, make bad calls that his coaches simply ignored, have inexplicable fits of anger, or call players from decades earlier to pinch-hit.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack also never installed a telephone in the dugout and instead would use a series of obtuse hand signs to signal his coaches on the field.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] According to infielder Ferris Fain, "He'd fall asleep for much of the game waving his score card, but he still had a few working nerve endings left in his big ol' neck waddle.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Anyone who dared wake him up was subjected to a hasty trial by the team's kangaroo court." For the most part, Mack's coaches handled in-game operations.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Nonetheless, despite calls inside and outside the organization to step down, Mack would not even consider firing himself.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Also during this time, Mack gave minority stakes in the team to his sons, Roy, Earle and Connie Jr.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Although Connie Jr. was nearly 20 years younger than Roy and Earle (he was the son of Connie Sr.'s second marriage), Mack intended to have all three of them inherit the team upon his death.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] He also intended for Earle, who had been assistant manager since 1924, to succeed him as manager.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] This decision would have dire consequences for the Athletics later on.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] During this time, Shibe Park was also becoming an increasing liability.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] While the facility had been state of the art when it opened in 1909, by the late 1940s, it had not been well maintained in some time.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] It was also not suited to automobile traffic, having been designed before the Ford Model T was introduced.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] To the surprise of most people in baseball, Mack managed not only to get out of the cellar in 1947, but actually finished with a winning record for the first time in 14 years.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] They contended for much of 1948, even managing to spend 49 days in first place.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, the turning point came on June 13, when pitcher Nels Potter, who had been a solid middle reliever for most of the season, blew a three-run lead in the first game of a doubleheader against the St.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] An enraged Mack ordered him off the team in front of a shocked clubhouse after the game.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics spent most of the summer in either first or second place.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack had previously released pitcher Bill Dietrich and his dismissal of Potter left the second place Athletics with only five healthy pitchers at that point.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] By the end of the year the team faded to fourth place.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The franchise would not be a factor in a pennant race again at that late date until 1969—their second year in Oakland.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Another winning record in 1949 sparked hopes that 1950—the 50th season for both the American League and Mack's tenure as manager of the Athletics—would bring a pennant at last.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] During that year, the team wore uniforms trimmed in blue and gold, in honor of the Golden Jubilee of "The Grand Old Man of Baseball." However, the 1950 season was an unmitigated disaster.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] They were only above .500 once all season (at 3–2), and a 5–17 May ended any hope of contention.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Before May was out, Mack's sons had agreed to ease their father out as manager.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] On May 26, it was announced that Mack would resign at the end of the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] On the same day, former Athletics star Jimmy Dykes, who had returned to the Athletics as a coach a year earlier, was named assistant manager and would transition to manager for the 1951 season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, for all practical purposes, Dykes took over as manager immediately; he was given control over the Athletics' day-to-day operations and became the team's main game-day operator.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Cochrane, who had been brought back as a coach earlier in the year, was named general manager, stripping Connie Sr. of his last direct authority over baseball matters.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Ultimately, the Athletics finished with the worst record in the majors at 52–102, 46 games out of first.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Mack's 50-year tenure is a North American professional sports record for manager/head coach that has never been threatened.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Unfortunately for the Athletics, the team continued to slide on the field.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Although the 1949 team set a major league record for double plays which still stands, this was more a reflection of the team's poor pitching staff allowing too many base runners.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] They would have only one winning record from 1951 to 1954—a fourth-place finish in 1952.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The nadir came in 1954, when the Athletics finished with a ghastly 51–103 record, easily the worst record in baseball and 60 games out of first.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] At the same time, the Phillies, who had been the definition of baseball futility for over 30 years, began a surprisingly quick climb to respectability.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics were the more popular team in Philadelphia for most of the first half of the century, even though for much of the last decade they had been as bad or worse than the Phillies.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] But in the 1940s, the Phillies began spending lavishly on young prospects.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1947, the Athletics finished fourth in the American League while the Phillies tied for the worst record in the National League.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Just three years later, the Athletics compiled the worst record in the majors and the Phillies went all the way to the 1950 World Series.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] It soon became obvious that the Phillies had passed the Athletics as Philadelphia's number-one team.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In the late 1940s, a power struggle developed between Roy and Earle on one side and Connie Jr. on the other.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Connie Jr., like many Athletics fans, had become disenchanted with his brothers' bargain-basement approach to running the team.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, Roy and Earle were not willing to modernize and refused to listen to their younger half-brother, whom they considered a mere child with no relevant opinion.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Compounding their disagreements was that they had different mothers.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] When it was apparent that Roy and Earle would not consider making what he considered to be critical reforms, Connie Jr. and his mother (who was angered at Connie Sr.'s refusal to give Connie Jr.'s sisters any role in the team) made an alliance with the Shibe heirs.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Connie Jr. began taking steps to upgrade the team and the park.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] One of the few things on which the two sides agreed was that it was time for Connie Sr. to step down as manager.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Matters came to a head in July 1950, when Connie Jr. and the Shibes decided to sell the team.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, Roy and Earle insisted that they have a 30-day option to buy out Connie Jr. and the Shibes before the team was put on the market.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Connie Jr. did not think Roy and Earle could get the $1.74 million required to buy him out, but Roy and Earle called their bluff by mortgaging the team to Connecticut General Life Insurance Company (now part of CIGNA) and pledging Shibe Park as collateral.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The shares of Connie Jr. and the Shibes were retired, ending the Shibes' half-century involvement with the Athletics and making Connie Sr., Roy and Earle the team's only shareholders.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Although his father remained nominal owner and team president, Roy, who had been vice president since 1936, now became operating head of the franchise, sharing day-to-day control with Earle.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, under the terms of the mortgage, the Athletics were now saddled with payments of $200,000 over the first five years, depriving them of badly needed capital that could have been used improving the team and the park.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Throughout the early 1950s, attendance plummeted, and there was nowhere near enough revenue to service the mortgage debt.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In response, Roy and Earle began cutting costs even further.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] They turned over the rent from the Phillies to Connecticut General and took cash advances from their concessions contractor.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The cost-cutting ramped up even further in the 1953–54 offseason, when they slashed over $100,000 from the player payroll, fired general manager Arthur Ehlers and replaced Dykes as manager with shortstop Eddie Joost.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] They also pared down the minor-league system to only six clubs.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, even with these measures, there still wasn't nearly enough money coming in to service the mortgage debt, and Roy and Earle began feuding with each other.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Despite the turmoil, some Athletics players shined on the field.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1951, Gus Zernial led the American League with 33 home runs, 129 runs scored, 68 extra-base hits, and 17 outfield assists; in 1952 he swatted 29 homers and bagged 100 RBI; in 1953 he hit 42 homers and drove in 108 runs.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 1952, left-handed pitcher Bobby Shantz won 24 games and was named the league's Most Valuable Player, and Ferris Fain won AL batting championships in 1951 (with a .344 average) and 1952 (with a .320 average).
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] His 1952 batting crown remains the last time an Athletic has led the league in hitting.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Joost was a solid fielder who had a good eye at the plate for generating walks and had an above-average on-base percentage as a result.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] All four players represented the American League in the All-Star Game.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Shantz might have won 30 games his best year 1952 but was hurt by a pitched ball on the wrist and was finished for the season.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] By the summer of 1954, it was obvious that the Athletics were on an irreversible slide into bankruptcy.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Earle and Roy decided that there was no choice but to sell their father's beloved team, and it was with great sorrow that the old man gave his approval for the sale.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Although several offers were put forward by Philadelphia interests, American League president Will Harridge was convinced that the team could never be viable in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The sparse crowds at Shibe had been a source of frustration for some time to the other AL owners, as they could not even begin to meet their expenses for trips to Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] As a result, Harridge had come to believe that the only way to resolve the "Philadelphia problem" was to move the Athletics elsewhere.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] For this reason, when Chicago businessman Arnold Johnson offered to buy the team, the other owners pressured Roy Mack to agree to the sale.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Johnson had very close ties to the Yankees; he not only owned Yankee Stadium but also owned Blues Stadium in Kansas City, home to the Yankees' top farm team.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Johnson intended to move the Athletics to a renovated Blues Stadium if he was cleared to buy them.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Yankees made no secret that they favored Johnson, and their backing gave him the upper hand with the other owners.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, on October 17, Roy Mack suddenly announced that the Athletics had been sold to a Philadelphia-based group headed by auto dealer John Crisconi, with Roy having an option to buy a minority stake.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The deal was to be approved at an American League owners' meeting on October 28.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] It looked headed for approval when rumors (reportedly planted by the Yankees) cropped up that the Crisconi group was underfinanced, and Johnson collared Roy Mack at Roy's home to persuade him that his original deal was better for his family in the long run.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] On October 28, the sale to the Crisconi group came up one vote short of the five needed for approval, with Roy Mack voting against the deal he had just negotiated.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] While Connie and Earle had joined Roy in signing the contract to sell their stakes to Crisconi, the league's rejection voided the deal.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] A day later, Connie Mack released an open letter to Athletics fans (one that was likely written by his wife) blasting the owners and Roy for sinking the deal to the Crisconi group.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, he conceded that he didn't have enough money to run the Athletics in 1955, and the Johnson deal was the only one that had any prospect of winning league approval.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] A few days later, the Macks sold the Athletics to Johnson for $3.5 million, $1.5 million for their shares plus $2 million in debt.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Selling Shibe Park—which had been renamed Connie Mack Stadium a year earlier—proved more difficult, but the Phillies reluctantly bought it.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The American League owners met again on November 8, and duly approved Johnson's bid to buy the Athletics.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Johnson's first act was to request permission to move to Kansas City.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] This proved more difficult, since it required a three-fourths majority.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] However, Detroit owner Spike Briggs was persuaded to change his vote, ending the Athletics' 54-year stay in Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics played the Phillies for the first time in interleague play in June 2003 at Veterans Stadium.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Phillies invited former Athletics Eddie Joost and Gus Zernial to the games.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Connie Mack's daughter Ruth Mack Clark attended the first game.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Senator Connie Mack III, Mack's grandson, threw out the first ball.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In turn, the Phillies played the Athletics in Oakland in June 2005.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The A's invited Eddie Joost to throw out the first pitch before the series opening game on June 17, 2005.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 2011 the Athletics visited the Phillies at Citizens Bank Park for an interleague series in which the Phillies took two out of three games.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] There remains a level of nostalgia for the Athletics in the Philadelphia region.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] A Philadelphia Athletics Historical Society exists with an active website, and a local company called Shibe Vintage Sports sells retro Philadelphia Athletics gear.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] By 2022, the Athletics franchise had played in Oakland, California longer than Philadelphia.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 2023, the team announced its intention to move to Las Vegas, Nevada effective in 2028.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] In 2024 the team announced that it would move to West Sacramento for the 2025–2027 seasons.
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] The Athletics have all of the numbers of the Hall-of-Fame players from the Philadelphia Athletics displayed at their stadium, as well as all of the years that the Philadelphia Athletics won World Championships (1910, 1911, 1913, 1929, and 1930).
[src:philadelphia-athletics/philadelphia-athletics] Also, from 1978 to 2003 (except 1983), the Philadelphia Phillies inducted one former Athletic (and one former Phillie) each year into the Philadelphia Baseball Wall of Fame at the then-existing Veterans Stadium.
